    {
      "text": "A 25-year-old man of Southeast Asian origin presents with mild anemia and fatigue. He has a history of similar episodes since adolescence. CBC shows : Hemoglobin: 9.2 g/dL, MCV: 68 fL, MCH: 22 pg/dl. Peripheral smear shows microcytosis, hypochromia, and numerous target cells. Supravital staining with brilliant cresyl blue reveals multiple small inclusions in RBCs giving a “golf ball” appearance. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "β-thalassemia minor"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "HbH disease"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Sideroblastic anemia"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Hereditary spherocytosis"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer is b: HbH disease </strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Golf ball” inclusions are precipitated β₄ tetramers in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a9268f2e1d16927771814cfef69cf4\">alpha</span> thalassemia/ HbH disease and are seen on <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8677c6e8251692777199817455a36f\">supravital</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b29a1a16ab1692777199ede1c6e28b\">stain</span> in α-thalassemia with three gene deletions.</li>\n\t<li>β-thalassemia minor has target cells on P.smear. Sideroblastic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"53bee2a41216927771814d7ec3a67f\">anemia</span> shows ring sideroblasts in bone marrow, not <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"255674f3271692777195c172d86daf\">peripheral</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6777533153169277719804fcbbf2d1\">smear</span> inclusions. Hereditary <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d30f4533661692777199385959bd9f\">spherocytosis</span> shows small RBC that lack central pallor.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>",
